Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
setSdpGroupAttribute(25.10)                        setSdpGroupAttribute(25.10)

Name
       setSdpGroupAttribute  - Sets or modifies the specified attributes of an
       existing SDP group

Syntax
       setSdpGroupAttribute

       [-help]

       [-flip {X Y XY NONE}]

       [-justifyBy {SW SE NW NE MID}]

        -name <sdp_name>

       [-orient {R0 MX MY R180 NONE}]

       [-origin {x y}]

       [-padding {x y}]

       [-skipSpace <spacing_pattern>]

       Sets or modifies the specified attributes of  an  existing  SDP  group.
       This  command can be used in anywhere in the flow after an SDP group is
       created.

Parameters
       -help  Prints a brief description that includes type and default infor-
              mation for each setSdpGroupAttribute parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the man command: man setSdpGroupAttribute.

       -flip {X Y XY NONE}
              Specifies that the SDP group should be flipped on  the  X  or  Y
              axis  along  with its elements. The alignment information is ad-
              justed accordingly.

       -justifyBy {SW SE NW NE MID}
              Specifies the anchor point that will be used to  align  the  SDP
              group.

       -name <sdp_name>
              Specifies the name of the SDP object.

       -orient {R0 MX MY R180 NONE}
              Specifies the orientation of the SDP object.

       -origin {x y}
              Specifies  the location of the top SDP group. It can be set only
              to the top group.

       -padding {x y}
              Specifies the edge extend value of the SDP bounding box in hori-
              zontal and vertical direction for the specified top  SDP  group.
              The tool uses the sum of the actual SDP bounding box and the ex-
              tended  value  to  place the SDP groups during global placement.
              This way, less SDP groups overlap because the tool  can  enlarge
              the SDP bounding box by using padding during global placement.

              For  example,  the following command specifies a padding of {5.0
              1.0} for the SDP top group named top_group1:

              setSdpGroupAttribute -name top_group1 -padding {5.0 1.0}

              Default: {0 0}

              Note: The padding is an attribute of each top SDP group. If  the
              specified  SDP  group name is not a top SDP group, the tool will
              give an error and return.

       -skipSpace <spacing_pattern>
              Specifies the spacing pattern of the SDP group.  The  value  for
              row  skipping  represents  the number of skipped rows. The value
              for column skipping represents the number of the first  vertical
              layer pitch. If the SDP group for which attributes are being set
              is of type space, the tool will accept a value for -skipSpace.

Examples
              *

                Consider  the  SDP  group,  sub_group1, with origin at {383.46
                628.88}. The following command will update the origin  of  the
                SDP group:

                setSdpGroupAttribute -name sub_group1 -origin {500 500}

                If  you  now  check, the origin will have been updated without
                the need for running the placeSdpGroup command:

                > puts "[dbGet top.fplan.topSdps.pt]"

                {500.28 497.84}

